description:
Every test should follow the AAA pattern for readability:

```ts
test('calculates total with discount', () => {
  // Arrange — set up preconditions
  const cart = createCart([item(10), item(20)]);
  const discount = percent(15);

  // Act — execute the behavior under test
  const total = cart.applyDiscount(discount);

  // Assert — verify the outcome
  expect(total).toBe(25.5);
});
```

If you can't clearly separate these three phases, the test is likely doing too much.

Tests should verify what the code does, not how it does it. Testing implementation details (private methods, internal state, call order) creates brittle tests that break on every refactor.

Bad — tests implementation:
```ts
expect(service._cache.size).toBe(1);
expect(fetchSpy).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
```

Good — tests behavior:
```ts
const first = await service.getUser(1);
const second = await service.getUser(1);
expect(first).toEqual(second); // caching works
```

Ask: 'If I refactor internals without changing behavior, will this test break?' If yes, it's testing implementation.

Mock external dependencies (HTTP APIs, databases, file system, clocks) at the boundary of your system. Don't mock internal modules or utility functions — let them run with real code.

```ts
// Good — mock the boundary (HTTP client)
const api = mockHttpClient({ '/users/1': { name: 'Alice' } });
const service = new UserService(api);
const user = await service.getById(1);
expect(user.name).toBe('Alice');

// Bad — mocking internal helper
jest.mock('./formatName'); // now you're testing nothing useful
```

Boundary mocks make tests fast and deterministic without sacrificing coverage of real logic.

Create factory functions that produce valid test objects with sensible defaults. Override only what matters for each test.

```ts
function buildUser(overrides: Partial<User> = {}): User {
  return {
    id: randomId(),
    name: 'Test User',
    email: 'test@example.com',
    role: 'viewer',
    createdAt: new Date('2024-01-01'),
    ...overrides,
  };
}

// In tests — only specify what matters
test('admins can delete', () => {
  const admin = buildUser({ role: 'admin' });
  expect(canDelete(admin)).toBe(true);
});
```

Factories reduce noise, prevent fragile tests, and make required vs incidental data obvious.

Each test should verify one behavior. Multiple assertions are fine when they verify different aspects of the same behavior. Multiple assertions testing different behaviors should be separate tests.

Good — one behavior, multiple asserts:
```ts
test('creates user with defaults', () => {
  const user = createUser({ name: 'Alice' });
  expect(user.name).toBe('Alice');
  expect(user.role).toBe('viewer');   // default
  expect(user.active).toBe(true);     // default
});
```

Bad — two behaviors in one test:
```ts
test('user lifecycle', () => {
  const user = createUser({ name: 'Alice' });
  expect(user.active).toBe(true);
  deactivateUser(user.id);
  expect(user.active).toBe(false); // separate behavior
});
```

Never use fixed delays (sleep, setTimeout) to wait for async operations. They're either too slow (wasted CI time) or too fast (flaky failures).

Bad:
```ts
await sleep(2000);
expect(screen.getByText('Done')).toBeVisible();
```

Good:
```ts
await waitFor(() => {
  expect(screen.getByText('Done')).toBeVisible();
}, { timeout: 5000 });
```

Other flaky test sources: shared state, network calls without mocks, time-dependent logic without fake clocks, random data without seeds. Fix the root cause — never retry-until-green.

Write tests before implementation in three steps:

1. RED — Write a failing test for the next piece of behavior:
```ts
test('should hash password before saving', async () => {
  const user = await createUser({ password: 'plain' });
  expect(user.password).not.toBe('plain');
  expect(user.password).toMatch(/^\$2b\$/);
});
```

2. GREEN — Write the minimum code to make it pass. No more.

3. REFACTOR — Clean up the implementation while keeping tests green.

TDD catches design issues early — if a test is hard to write, the API is hard to use. Small cycles (5-10 min) keep you focused and prevent over-engineering.

Don't write e2e or browser tests to verify business logic. If you need to check that a discount calculation is correct, test the calculation function directly — not by filling out a form, clicking submit, and reading the total from the DOM.

```ts
// Bad — slow, brittle, tests too many things at once
test('discount works', async () => {
  await page.fill('#amount', '100');
  await page.click('#apply-discount');
  expect(await page.textContent('#total')).toBe('$85.00');
});

// Good — fast, focused, tests the actual logic
test('applies 15% discount', () => {
  expect(applyDiscount(100, 0.15)).toBe(85);
});
```

Push logic tests down to the unit level. Use e2e only for user flow validation.

When testing the same behavior with different inputs, use parameterized tests (test.each / it.each) instead of duplicating test bodies.

```ts
test.each([
  ['empty string', '', false],
  ['valid email', 'a@b.com', true],
  ['missing @', 'ab.com', false],
  ['missing domain', 'a@', false],
  ['unicode local', 'ñ@b.com', true],
])('isValidEmail(%s) returns %s', (_label, input, expected) => {
  expect(isValidEmail(input)).toBe(expected);
});
```

Benefits: less duplication, easy to add cases, each case reports separately on failure. Use for validators, parsers, formatters, and any pure function with varied inputs.
